snippet.textDisplay: In case anyone is interested to try Chapaguri using these instant noodles, most people in Korea make it a little differently. The instant noodles company (Nongshim) even put out a recipe. You should boil the noodles and dry vegetable flakes together in plain water (don't add any soup powder yet), drain most of the water, and THEN add both packets of soup powder and mix them together. Then the olive oil goes on at the end. The flavor will be stronger and it should be darker in color than the one in this video. Nongshim also suggests using only half of the Neoguri powder because the taste is pretty strong.
snippet.textOriginal: In case anyone is interested to try Chapaguri using these instant noodles, most people in Korea make it a little differently. The instant noodles company (Nongshim) even put out a recipe. You should boil the noodles and dry vegetable flakes together in plain water (don't add any soup powder yet), drain most of the water, and THEN add both packets of soup powder and mix them together. Then the olive oil goes on at the end. The flavor will be stronger and it should be darker in color than the one in this video. Nongshim also suggests using only half of the Neoguri powder because the taste is pretty strong.

snippet.textDisplay: The recipe is almost there, speaking as a Korean ^^. The noodles from both packs should be put in when the water is boiling. After the noodle is about half way cooked, it should be drained. Leave about 4 to 5 table spoons of water behind. Add all of the Jjapagetti sauce and half of the neoguri sauce (unless you want it more seasoned) and all the flakes. Add the seared meat while before stirring. Blend all the ingredients together. When everything is coated ( the Jjapagetti powder will thicken the moisture left in the saucepan). Ready to serve !
